## BURN ML FRAMEWORK

When using the Burn ML framework:

1. FOLLOW the Burn tensor API conventions
2. USE autodiff for gradient-based operations
3. LEVERAGE Burn's device abstraction for cross-platform compatibility
4. IMPLEMENT custom operations through the Burn operator API
5. OPTIMIZE memory usage with appropriate tensor shapes and types

ONE SOLUTION ONLY:
```rust
// Burn ML pattern
use burn::{
    module::Module,
    tensor::{backend::Backend, Tensor},
};

// Define a simple module
#[derive(Module, Debug)]
pub struct FeatureExtractor<B: Backend> {
    conv1: Conv2d<B>,
    conv2: Conv2d<B>,
    pool: MaxPool2d,
}

impl<B: Backend> FeatureExtractor<B> {
    pub fn new(config: &Config) -> Self {
        let device = &config.device;
        
        Self {
            conv1: Conv2d::new(
                3, 16, 
                Conv2dConfig::new(3, 1, 1, 1),
                device,
            ),
            conv2: Conv2d::new(
                16, 32,
                Conv2dConfig::new(3, 1, 1, 1),
                device,
            ),
            pool: MaxPool2d::new(MaxPool2dConfig::new(2, 2)),
        }
    }
    
    pub fn forward(&self, input: Tensor<B, 4>) -> Tensor<B, 4> {
        let x = self.conv1.forward(input);
        let x = x.relu();
        let x = self.pool.forward(x);
        let x = self.conv2.forward(x);
        let x = x.relu();
        let x = self.pool.forward(x);
        x
    }
}
```

