## WEBGPU USAGE

When working with WebGPU:

1. USE Burn's WebGPU backend when possible
2. UNDERSTAND compute vs rendering pipelines
3. FOLLOW the data-oriented design for shader inputs
4. MINIMIZE CPU-GPU data transfers
5. IMPLEMENT fallbacks for unsupported WebGPU features
6. HANDLE device capability differences explicitly

ONE SOLUTION ONLY:
```rust
// WebGPU pattern through Burn
use burn::backend::wgpu::{WgpuBackend, WgpuDevice};

type Backend = WgpuBackend<f32>;

pub async fn initialize_webgpu() -> Result<WgpuDevice, BrushError> {
    // Create device with appropriate features
    let device = WgpuDevice::builder()
        .with_features(wgpu::Features::SHADER_F16)
        .with_limits(wgpu::Limits::default())
        .build()
        .await
        .map_err(|e| BrushError::Gpu(e.to_string()))?;
    
    Ok(device)
}

pub fn create_processing_pipeline<B: Backend>(
    device: &B::Device,
    config: &ProcessingConfig,
) -> ProcessingPipeline<B> {
    // Create model with appropriate tensors
    let model = ProcessingModel::new(ModelConfig {
        device: device.clone(),
        dimensions: config.dimensions,
        // Other configuration...
    });
    
    ProcessingPipeline::new(model, device)
}
```

